Load country-wide data by ISCO

Source: R/pv_load_cr.R
pv_cr_monthlypay_isco.Rd

Load country-wide data by ISCO

Usage

pv_cr_monthlypay_isco(path, sheet = 1)

Arguments

path

path to one or more Excel files (character vector length one or more). Will be file with "CR_" and either "PLS" or "MZS" in the name

sheet

which sheet to open. Will be 1 in files with only one sheet ("CR_204_MZS_M8r.xlsx") and 7 in comprehensive file ("CR_204_MZS.xlsx")

Value

a tibble

Examples

pv_cr_monthlypay_isco(system.file("extdata", "CR_204_MZS_M8r.xlsx", package = "ispv"), 1)
#> Warning: TRE pattern compilation error 'Invalid regexp'
#> Error in regexpr("(?<=\\_)2[0-9][2,4](?=\\_) ", ispv_all$file): invalid regular expression '(?<=\_)2[0-9][2,4](?=\_) ', reason 'Invalid regexp'
pv_cr_monthlypay_isco(system.file("extdata", "CR_204_MZS.xlsx", package = "ispv"), 7)
#> Warning: TRE pattern compilation error 'Invalid regexp'
#> Error in regexpr("(?<=\\_)2[0-9][2,4](?=\\_) ", ispv_all$file): invalid regular expression '(?<=\_)2[0-9][2,4](?=\_) ', reason 'Invalid regexp'
pv_cr_monthlypay_isco(system.file("extdata", "CR_204_PLS_M8r.xlsx", package = "ispv"), 1)
#> Warning: TRE pattern compilation error 'Invalid regexp'
#> Error in regexpr("(?<=\\_)2[0-9][2,4](?=\\_) ", ispv_all$file): invalid regular expression '(?<=\_)2[0-9][2,4](?=\_) ', reason 'Invalid regexp'
